Let's begin by finding our value of r using the formula given as follows:\begin{align*}
\label{eq:polarCoordinate}
r&=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}\\ &= \sqrt{0^{2}+3^{2}} \\&= \sqrt{9}\\ &=\color{blue}{3}\end{align*} Now let us determine what angle corresponds to when x equals zero.\begin{align*}(c)& =\tan^{-1}(\dfrac{y}{x}) && y & = 3 , x & = 0 \\ (\mbox{because }x = 0, ) &\qquad f(x)=\text{undefined but }\;\lim_{h\to 0^-}\dfrac{f(0+h)}{h}=&\quad \infty\\ \therefore \theta & =\tan^{-1}\left(\infty\right)\\& =\frac{\pi }{2}\quad .\end{align*} Thus $$\boxed{\text {the polar coordinate representation of the point}}\, \,(0,3)\,$$is $$(r,\theta)=\boxed{(3, \frac{\pi }{2})}$$ An alternative approach would also work here since you could simply evaluate ar
